ersden, Kent, Inglaterra":"Bethersden, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bethersden, Kent, England":"Bethersden, Kent, England"},"en":{"1335–1414":"1335–1414","1330–1400":"1330–1400","1360–1417":"1360–1417","1414":"1414","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1417":"1417","Bethersden, Kent, Inglaterra":"Bethersden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Bethersden, Kent, England":"Bethersden, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lovelace","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Loveless  . The spelling is apparently theresult of folk etymology, which understood the word as a nickname fora dandy fond of lace. The modern sense of this word is, however, notattested until the 16th century and at the time of surname formationit meant only ‘cord’ or ‘shoelace’."],"variants":[{"name":"Loveless","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>loveles</i> ‘loveless, without love’, probably in the sense ‘fancy free’.","some early examples, such as Richard Lovelas (Kent 1344), may have as their second element Middle English <i>las(se)</i> ‘girl’, ‘maiden’."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Joan Lovelace was born in 1335, in Bethersden, Kent, England. She had at least 1 son with John Lovelace II. She died in 1414, in her hometown, at the age of 79."},"et":{"1335–1414":"1335–1414","1330–1400":"1330–1400","1360–1417":"1360–1417","1414":"1414","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1417":"1417","Bethersden, Kent, Inglaterra":"Bethersden, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bethersden, Kent, England":"Bethersden, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1335–1414":"1335–1414","1330–1400":"1330–1400","1360–1417":"1360–1417","1414":"1414","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1417":"1417","Bethersden, Kent, Inglaterra":"Bethersden, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bethersden, Kent, England":"Bethersden, Kent, England"},"fr":{"1335–1414":"1335–1414","1330–1400":"1330–1400","1360–1417":"1360–1417","1414":"1414","1337":"1337","1335":"1335","1400":"1400","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1417":"1417","Bethersden, Kent, In